<!-- END APPRAISAL FORM -->
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      I work the western corridor regularly and understand how buyers weigh Kenmore against its neighbours. Many arrive after doing thorough comparisons with Indooroopilly and Toowong and finding that the price differential makes Kenmore the logical next step. What they find is a suburb that delivers on the core western suburbs brief: space, good schools, a leafy streetscape, and a community feel that comes from decades of stable family ownership. Upgraders from Indooroopilly and Toowong are a consistent presence, and so are interstate buyers who have done their research on Brisbane's western corridor and identified Kenmore as a relative value proposition within an established family catchment.
    </p>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Kenmore Village Shopping Centre handles the everyday retail brief, and Moggill Road and Kenmore Road carry bus services into the CBD and down to Indooroopilly station. The suburb is car-dependent for school runs, which is simply a practical reality of western suburbs living, but the off-peak drive to the CBD runs to around 20 minutes and the proximity to Mt Coot-tha means residents have exceptional bushland access on their doorstep. The housing mix spans original lowset brick homes on larger blocks through to contemporary renovations and newer builds, with the best results coming from properties that combine a genuine land holding with presentation that reflects the suburb's family-buyer profile.
    </p>
    <div style="display:flex; gap:1.5rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
